{"title_page": "Dirac matter", "text_new": "{{technical|date=November 2019}}\n\nThe term '''Dirac matter''' refers to a class of [[condensed matter]] systems which can be effectively described by the [[Dirac equation]]. Even though the [[Dirac equation]] itself was formulated for [[fermions]], the quasi-particles present within Dirac matter can be of any statistics. As a consequence, Dirac matter can be distinguished in [[fermionic]], [[bosonic]] or [[anyon]]ic Dirac matter. Prominent examples of Dirac matter are [[Graphene]], [[topological insulators]], Dirac semimetals, [[Weyl semimetal]]s, various [[high-temperature superconductors]] with <math>d</math>-wave pairing and [[Helium-3|liquid Helium-3]]. The effective theory of such systems is classified by a specific choice of the [[Dirac mass]], the Dirac velocity, the [[Dirac matrices]] and the [[space-time curvature]]. The universal treatment of the class of Dirac matter in terms of an effective theory leads to a common features with respect to the [[density of states]], the [[heat capacity]] and impurity scattering.\n\n== Definition ==\nMembers of the class of Dirac matter differ significantly in nature. However, all examples of Dirac matter are unified by similarities within the algebraic structure of an effective theory describing them.\n\n=== General ===\n\nThe general definition of Dirac matter is a condensed matter system where the [[quasi-particle]] excitations can be described in curved spacetime by the generalised Dirac equation:\n:<math>\n \\left[i \\hbar v_D \\gamma^a e_a^\\mu d_\\mu(p) - m v_D^2\\right]\\Psi = 0.\n</math>\nIn the above definition <math>d_\\mu</math> denotes a [[covariant vector]] depending on the <math>(d+1)</math>-dimensional momentum <math>p</math> (<math>d</math> space <math>+ 1</math> time dimension), <math>e_a^\\mu</math> is the [[vierbein]] describing the curvature of the space, <math>m</math> the [[quasi-particle]] mass and <math>v_D</math> the Dirac velocity. Note that since in Dirac matter the Dirac equation gives the effective theory of the quasiparticles, the energy from the mass term is <math>m v_D^2</math>, not the rest mass <math>m c^2</math> of a massive particle. <math>\\gamma^\\mu</math> refers to a set of [[Dirac matrices]], where the defining for the construction is given by the anticommutation relation,\n:<math>\n  \\left\\{\\gamma^\\mu,\\gamma^\\nu \\right\\} = \\gamma^\\mu\\gamma^\\nu + \\gamma^\\nu\\gamma^\\mu = \\eta^{\\mu\\nu} I_d.\n</math>\n<math>\\eta^{\\mu\\nu}</math> is the [[Minkowski metric]] with signature (+ - - -) and <math>I_d</math> is the <math>d\\times d</math>-dimensional unit matrix.\nIn all equations, implicit summation over <math>a</math> and <math>\\mu</math> is used ([[Einstein convention]]). Furthermore, <math>\\Psi</math> is the [[wavefunction]]. The unifying feature of all Dirac matter is the matrix structure of the equation describing the quasi-particle excitations.\n\nIn the limit where <math>d_\\mu(p) = D_\\mu</math>, i.e. the [[covariant derivative]], conventional Dirac matter is obtained. However, this general definition allows the description of matter with higher order dispersion relations and in curved spacetime as long as the effective [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]] exhibits the [[matrix (mathematics)|matrix]] structure specific to the [[Dirac equation]].\n\n=== Common (conventional) ===\n\nThe majority of experimental realisations of Dirac matter to date are in the limit of <math>d_\\mu (p) = D_\\mu</math> which therefore defines conventional Dirac matter in which the quasiparticles are described by the [[Dirac equation in curved spacetime|Dirac equation in curved space-time]],\n:<math>\n \\left[i \\hbar v_D \\gamma^a e_a^\\mu D_\\mu - m v_D^2\\right]\\Psi = 0.\n</math>\nHere, <math>D_\\mu</math> denotes the [[covariant derivative]]. As an example, for the flat metric, the energy of a free Dirac particle differs significantly from the classical kinetic energy where energy is proportional to momentum squared:\n:<math>\n\\begin{align}\n\\mathrm{Free~Dirac~particle: \\;} E &= \\pm \\sqrt{\\hbar^2 v_D^2\\mathbf{k}^2+m^2c^4} \\\\\n\\mathrm{Kinetic\\; energy: \\;} E &= \\frac{m |\\mathbf{v}|^2}{2} = \\frac{|\\mathbf{k}|^2}{2m}.\n\\end{align}\n</math>\nThe Dirac velocity <math>v_D</math> gives the gradient of the <math>E-k</math> dispersion at large momenta <math>k</math>, <math>m</math> is the mass of particle or object. In the case of massless Dirac matter, such as the fermionic quasiparticles in [[graphene]] or [[Weyl semimetal]]s, the energy-momentum relation is linear,\n:<math>\n E(\\mathbf{k}) = \\hbar v_D |\\mathbf{k}|\n</math>\n\nTherefore, conventional Dirac matter includes all systems that have a linear crossing or linear behavior in some region of the energy-momentum relation. They are characterised by features that resemble an 'X', sometimes tilted or skewed and sometimes with a gap between the upper <math>\\vee</math> and lower <math>\\wedge</math> parts (the turning points of which become rounded if the origin of the gap is a mass term).\n\nThe general features and some specific examples of conventional Dirac matter are discussed in the following sections.\n\n== General properties of Dirac matter ==\n\n=== Technological relevance and tuning of Dirac matter ===\n\n[[File:Tuning of Dirac matter.png|thumb|Tuning of Dirac matter: As the density of states is well defined, the density of states at the Fermi level (for fermionic Dirac matter) can be nicely tuned by shifting the chemical potential <math>\\mu</math>. Additionally, introducing a mass term <math>m</math> leads to a gap between the two cones and the dispersion becomes quadratic near <math>k=0</math>.]]\n\nDirac matter, especially fermionic Dirac matter has much potential for technological applications. For example, 2010's [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] was awarded to [[Andre Geim]] and [[Konstantin Novoselov]] \"for groundbreaking experiments regarding the material graphene\". Within the official press release of the [[Swedish Royal Academy of Science]] it is stated that<ref name=\"nobelprize\">[https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/2010/press.pdf The Nobel Prize in Physics 2010]</ref>\n{{Quote\n|text=\n[...] a vast variety of practical applications now appear possible including the creation of new materials and the manufacture of innovative electronics. Graphene transistors are predicted to be substantially faster than today\u2019s silicon transistors and result in more efficient computers.\n|author=Swedish Royal Academy of Science\n}}\n\nIn general, the properties of massless fermionic Dirac matter can be controlled by shifting the [[chemical potential]] by means of [[doping (semiconductor)|doping]] or within a [[field effect (semiconductor)|field effect]] setup. By tuning the [[chemical potential]], it is possible to have a precise control of the number of states present, since the [[density of states]] varies in a well-defined way with energy.\n\nAdditionally, depending on the specific realization of the Dirac material, it may be possible to introduce a mass term <math>m</math> that opens a gap in the spectrum - a [[band gap]]. In general, the mass term is the result of breaking a specific symmetry of the system. The size of the [[band gap]] can be controlled precisely by controlling the strength of the mass term.\n\n=== Density of states ===\nThe [[density of states]] of <math>d</math>-dimensional Dirac matter near the Dirac point scales as <math>N(\\epsilon)\\propto |\\epsilon|^{d-1}</math> where <math>\\epsilon</math> is the particle energy.<ref name=\"wehling2014dirac\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/00018732.2014.927109|title=Dirac materials|journal=Advances in Physics|volume=63|issue=1|page=1|year=2014|last1=Wehling|first1=T.O|last2=Black-Schaffer|first2=A.M|last3=Balatsky|first3=A.V|arxiv=1405.5774}}</ref> The vanishing density of states for quasiparticles in Dirac matter mimics [[semimetal]] physics for physical dimension <math>d>1</math>. In the two-dimensional systems such as graphene and topological insulators, the density of states gives a V shape, compared with the constant value for massive particles with dispersion <math>E=k^2/2m</math>.\n\nExperimental measurement of the density of states near the Dirac point by standard techniques such as scanning tunnelling microscopy often differ from the theoretical form due to the effects of disorder and interactions.<ref name=\"principi2011tunneling\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.ssc.2012.04.040|title=The tunneling density-of-states of interacting massless Dirac fermions|journal=Solid State Communications|volume=152|issue=15|page=1456|year=2012|last1=Principi|first1=A|last2=Polini|first2=Marco|last3=Asgari|first3=Reza|last4=MacDonald|first4=A.H|arxiv=1111.3822|bibcode=2012SSCom.152.1456P}}</ref>\n\n=== Specific heat ===\nSpecific heat, the [[heat capacity]] per unit mass, describes the energy required to change the temperature of a sample. The low-temperature electronic [[specific heat]] of Dirac matter is <math>C(T\\to 0)\\sim T^d</math> which is different from <math>C(T\\to 0)\\sim T</math> encountered for normal metals.<ref name=\"wehling2014dirac\"/> Therefore, for systems whose physical dimension is greater than 1, the specific heat can provide a clear signature of the underlying Dirac nature of the quasiparticles.\n\n=== Landau quantization ===\n[[Landau quantization]] refers to the quantization of the cyclotron orbits of charged particles in magnetic fields. As a result, the charged particles can only occupy orbits with discrete energy values, called Landau levels. For 2-dimensional systems with a perpendicular magnetic field, the energy for Landau-levels for ordinary matter described the Schr\u00f6dinger equation and Dirac matter are given by<ref name=\"wehling2014dirac\"/>\n:<math>\n\\begin{align}\n\\mathrm{Ordinary\\;matter: \\;} E &= \\hbar \\omega_c \\left(n+\\frac{1}{2} \\right), \\\\\n\\mathrm{Dirac\\;Matter: \\;} E &= \\hbar \\omega_c \\sqrt{|n|}.\n\\end{align}\n</math>\nHere, <math>\\omega_c</math> is the [[cyclotron frequency]] which is linearly dependent of the applied magnetic field and the charge of the particle. There are two distinct features between the Landau level quantization for 2D Schr\u00f6dinger fermions (ordinary matter) and 2D Dirac fermions. First, the energy for Schr\u00f6dinger fermions is linearly dependent with respect to the integer quantum number <math>n</math>, whereas it exhibits a square-root dependence for the Dirac fermions. This key difference plays an important role in the experimental verification of Dirac matter.<ref name=\"novoselov2005two\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nature04233|pmid=16281030|title=Two-dimensional gas of massless Dirac fermions in graphene|journal=Nature|volume=438|issue=7065|pages=197\u2013200|year=2005|last1=Novoselov|first1=K. S|last2=Geim|first2=A. K|last3=Morozov|first3=S. V|last4=Jiang|first4=D|last5=Katsnelson|first5=M. I|last6=Grigorieva|first6=I. V|last7=Dubonos|first7=S. V|last8=Firsov|first8=A. A|arxiv=cond-mat/0509330|bibcode=2005Natur.438..197N|hdl=2066/33126}}</ref><ref name=\"li2007observation\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nphys653|title=Observation of Landau levels of Dirac fermions in graphite|journal=Nature Physics|volume=3|issue=9|page=623|year=2007|last1=Li|first1=Guohong|last2=Andrei|first2=Eva Y|arxiv=0705.1185|bibcode=2007NatPh...3..623L}}</ref> Furthermore, for <math>n=0</math> there exists a 0 energy level for Dirac fermions which is independent of the cyclotron frequency <math>\\omega_c</math> and with that of the applied magnetic field. For example, the existence of the zeroth Landau level gives rise to a [[quantum Hall effect]] where the Hall conductance in quantized at half-integer values.<ref name=\"chen2008charged\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nphys935|title=Charged-impurity scattering in graphene|journal=Nature Physics|volume=4|issue=5|page=377|year=2008|last1=Chen|first1=J.-H|last2=Jang|first2=C|last3=Adam|first3=S|last4=Fuhrer|first4=M. S|last5=Williams|first5=E. D|last6=Ishigami|first6=M|arxiv=0708.2408|bibcode=2008NatPh...4..377C}}</ref><ref name=\"wehling2014dirac\"/>\n\n== Fermionic Dirac matter ==\nIn the context of Fermionic quasiparticles, the Dirac velocity is identical to the Fermi velocity; in bosonic systems, no Fermi velocity exists, so the Dirac velocity is a more general property of such systems.\n\n=== Graphene ===\n[[Graphene]] is a 2-dimensional crystalline [[allotrope]] of [[carbon]], where the carbon atoms are arranged on a [[hexagonal lattice]].\nEach carbon atom forms <math>\\sigma</math>-bonds to the three neighboring atoms that lie in the graphene plane at angles of 120<math>^\\circ</math>. These bonds are mediated by three of carbon's four [[electrons]] while the fourth electron, which occupies a <math>\\mathrm{p}_z</math> [[Atomic orbital|orbital]], mediates an out-of-plane [[pi-bond|{{pi}}-bond]] that leads to the [[Electronic band structure|electronic bands]] at the [[Fermi level]]. The unique transport properties and the [[semimetal]]lic state of graphene are the result of the delocalized electrons occupying these p<math>_z</math> orbitals.<ref name=\"abergel2010properties\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/00018732.2010.487978|title=Properties of graphene: A theoretical perspective|journal=Advances in Physics|volume=59|issue=4|pages=261\u2013482|year=2010|last1=Abergel|first1=D.S.L|last2=Apalkov|first2=V|last3=Berashevich|first3=J|last4=Ziegler|first4=K|last5=Chakraborty|first5=Tapash|arxiv=1003.0391}}</ref>\n\nThe semimetallic state corresponds to a linear crossing of energy bands at the <math>K</math> and <math>K'</math> points of graphene's hexagonal [[Brillouin zone]]. At these two points, the electronic structure can be effectively described by the [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]]\n:<math>\n{\\cal H} = \\hbar v_D \\left(\\tau k_x \\sigma_x + k_y \\sigma_y \\right). \n</math>\nHere, <math>\\sigma_x</math> and <math>\\sigma_y</math> are two of the three [[Pauli matrices]].\nThe factor <math>\\tau=+/-</math> indicates whether the Hamiltonian describes is centred on the <math>K</math> or <math>K'</math> valley at the corner of hexagonal [[Brillouin zone]]. For graphene, the Dirac velocity is about <math>\\hbar v_D \\approx 5.8</math> eV <math>\\AA</math>.<ref name=\"abergel2010properties\"/> An energy gap in the dispersion of graphene can be obtained from a low-energy Hamiltionain of the form \n:<math>\n\\begin{align}\n{\\cal H} = \\hbar v_D (\\tau k_x \\sigma_x + k_y\\sigma_y) + M \\sigma_z,\n\\end{align}\n</math>\nwhich now contains a mass term <math>M</math>. There are several distinct ways of introducing a mass term, and the results have different characteristics.<ref name=\"haldane\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.61.2015|pmid=10038961|title=Model for a Quantum Hall Effect without Landau Levels: Condensed-Matter Realization of the \"Parity Anomaly\"|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=61|issue=18|pages=2015\u20132018|year=1988|last1=Haldane|first1=F. D. M|bibcode=1988PhRvL..61.2015H|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"kane-mele\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.95.226801|pmid=16384250|title=Quantum Spin Hall Effect in Graphene|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=95|issue=22|pages=226801|year=2005|last1=Kane|first1=C. L|last2=Mele|first2=E. J|arxiv=cond-mat/0411737|bibcode=2005PhRvL..95v6801K}}</ref> The most practical approach for creating a gap (introducing a mass term) is to break the sublattice symmetry of the lattice where each carbon atom is slightly different to its nearest but identical to its next-nearest neighbours; an effect that may result from substrate effects.\n\n=== Topological insulators ===\nA [[topological insulator]] is a material that behaves as an insulator in its interior (bulk) but whose surface contains conducting states. This property represents a non-trivial, symmetry protected [[topological order]]. As a consequence, electrons in topological insulators can only move along the [[Interface (matter)|surface]] of the material. In the bulk of a non-interacting topological insulator, the [[Fermi level]] is positioned within the gap between the [[valence and conduction bands|conduction and valence bands]]. On the surface, there are special states within the bulk [[energy gap]] which can be effectively described by a Dirac Hamiltonian: \n:<math>\n\\begin{align}\n{\\cal H} = \\hbar v_{D} (\\mathbf{k}\\times \\mathbf{\\sigma})\\cdot\\hat{\\mathbf{z}}\n\\end{align}\n</math>\nwhere <math>\\hat{\\mathbf{z}}</math> is normal to the surface and <math>{\\mathbf{\\sigma}}</math> is in the real [[spin (physics)|spin]] basis. However, if we rotate spin by a [[unitary operator]], <math>U={\\rm diag}[1,i]</math>, we will end up with the standard notation of Dirac Hamiltonian, <math>{\\cal H} = \\hbar v_{D} {\\mathbf{\\sigma}}\\cdot {\\mathbf{k}}</math>.   \nSuch Dirac cones emerging on the surface of 3-dimensional crystals were observed in experiment, e.g.: [[bismuth selenide]] (Bi<math>_2</math>Se<math>_3</math>),<ref name=\"xia2009observation\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nphys1274|title=Observation of a large-gap topological-insulator class with a single Dirac cone on the surface|journal=Nature Physics|volume=5|issue=6|pages=398\u2013402|year=2009|last1=Xia|first1=Y|last2=Qian|first2=D|last3=Hsieh|first3=D|last4=Wray|first4=L|last5=Pal|first5=A|last6=Lin|first6=H|last7=Bansil|first7=A|last8=Grauer|first8=D|last9=Hor|first9=Y. S|last10=Cava|first10=R. J|last11=Hasan|first11=M. Z|arxiv=0908.3513|bibcode=2009NatPh...5..398X}}</ref> [[tin telluride]] (SnTe).<ref name=\"tanaka2012experimental\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nphys2442|title=Experimental realization of a topological crystalline insulator in Sn ''Te''|journal=Nature Physics|volume=8|issue=11|page=800|year=2012|last1=Tanaka|first1=Y|last2=Ren|first2=Zhi|last3=Sato|first3=T|last4=Nakayama|first4=K|last5=Souma|first5=S|last6=Takahashi|first6=T|last7=Segawa|first7=Kouji|last8=Ando|first8=Yoichi|arxiv=1206.5399|bibcode=2012NatPh...8..800T}}</ref>\n\n=== Transition metal dichalcogenides (TMDCs) ===\n[[File:Dispersions of transition metal dichalcogenides.png|thumb|While they are gapped, near the <math>K</math> and <math>K^\\prime</math> points of their hexagonal Brilliouin zone, the dispersions of transition metal dichalcogenides can be described by a massive Dirac equation with additional spin-orbit coupling terms that lead to spin-splitting in the valence band.]]\nThe low-energy properties some semiconducting [[transition metal dichalcogenide monolayers]],\ncan be described by a two-dimensional massive (gapped) Dirac Hamiltonian with an additional term describing a strong [[spin\u2013orbit coupling]]:<ref name=\"Xiao12\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.108.196802|pmid=23003071|title=Coupled Spin and Valley Physics in Monolayers ofMoS2and Other Group-VI Dichalcogenides|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=108|issue=19|pages=196802|year=2012|last1=Xiao|first1=Di|last2=Liu|first2=Gui-Bin|last3=Feng|first3=Wanxiang|last4=Xu|first4=Xiaodong|last5=Yao|first5=Wang|arxiv=1112.3144|bibcode=2012PhRvL.108s6802X}}</ref><ref name=\"rostami_prb_2013\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.88.085440|title=Effective lattice Hamiltonian for monolayer MoS2: Tailoring electronic structure with perpendicular electric and magnetic fields|journal=Physical Review B|volume=88|issue=8|pages=085440|year=2013|last1=Rostami|first1=Habib|last2=Moghaddam|first2=Ali G|last3=Asgari|first3=Reza|arxiv=1302.5901|bibcode=2013PhRvB..88h5440R}}</ref><ref name=\"Andor_prb_2013\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.88.045416|title=Monolayer MoS2: Trigonal warping, the\u0393valley, and spin-orbit coupling effects|journal=Physical Review B|volume=88|issue=4|pages=045416|year=2013|last1=Korm\u00e1nyos|first1=Andor|last2=Z\u00f3lyomi|first2=Viktor|last3=Drummond|first3=Neil D|last4=Rakyta|first4=P\u00e9ter|last5=Burkard|first5=Guido|last6=Fal'Ko|first6=Vladimir I|arxiv=1304.4084|bibcode=2013PhRvB..88d5416K}}</ref><ref name=\"Liu_prb_2013\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.88.085433|title=Three-band tight-binding model for monolayers of group-VIB transition metal dichalcogenides|journal=Physical Review B|volume=88|issue=8|pages=085433|year=2013|last1=Liu|first1=Gui-Bin|last2=Shan|first2=Wen-Yu|last3=Yao|first3=Yugui|last4=Yao|first4=Wang|last5=Xiao|first5=Di|arxiv=1305.6089|bibcode=2013PhRvB..88h5433L}}</ref> \n:<math>\n\\begin{align}\n{\\cal H} = \\hbar v_{D} (\\tau k_x \\sigma_x+k_y\\sigma_y)+\\Delta\\sigma_z+\\lambda(1-\\sigma_z)\\tau s+(\\alpha+\\beta\\sigma_z)(k_x^2+k_y^2).\n\\end{align}\n</math>\n\nThe spin-orbit coupling <math>\\lambda</math> provides a large spin-splitting in the valence band and <math>s</math> indicates the [[spin (physics)|spin]] degree of freedom. As for graphene, <math>\\tau</math> gives the valley degree of freedom - whether near the <math>K</math> or <math>K^\\prime</math> point of the hexagonal Brillouin zone. Transition metal dichalcogenide monolayers are often discussed in reference to potential applications in [[valleytronics]].\n\n=== Weyl semimetals ===\n[[Weyl semimetal]]s, for example tantalum arsenide (TaAs),<ref name=Huang>{{cite journal|last1=Huang|first1=S.-M.|first2=S.-Y.|last2=Xu|first3=I.|last3=Belopolski|first4=C.-C.|last4=Lee|first5=G.|last5=Chang|first6=B. K.|last6=Wang|first7=N.|last7=Alidoust|first8=G.|last8=Bian|first9=M.|last9=Neupane|first10=C.|last10=Zhang|first11=S.|last11=Jia|first12=A.|last12=Bansil|first13=H.|last13=Lin|first14=M. Z.|last14=Hasan|title=A Weyl Fermion semimetal with surface Fermi arcs in the transition metal monopnictide TaAs class|journal=Nature Communications|date=2015|volume=6|page=7373|doi=10.1038/ncomms8373|pmid=26067579|pmc=4490374|bibcode = 2015NatCo...6.7373H }}</ref><ref name=\"PhysRevX.5.011029\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevX.5.011029|title=Weyl Semimetal Phase in Noncentrosymmetric Transition-Metal Monophosphides|journal=Physical Review X|volume=5|issue=1|pages=011029|year=2015|last1=Weng|first1=Hongming|last2=Fang|first2=Chen|last3=Fang|first3=Zhong|last4=Bernevig|first4=B. Andrei|last5=Dai|first5=Xi|arxiv=1501.00060|bibcode=2015PhRvX...5a1029W}}</ref><ref name=Xu>{{cite journal|last1=Xu|first1=S.-Y.|first2=I.|last2=Belopolski|first3=N.|last3=Alidoust|first4=M.|last4=Neupane|first5=G.|last5=Bian|first6=C.|last6=Zhang|first7=R.|last7=Sankar|first8=G.|last8=Chang|first9=Z.|last9=Yuan|first10=C.-C.|last10=Lee|first11=S.-M.|last11=Huang|first12=H.|last12=Zheng|first13=J.|last13=Ma|first14=D. S.|last14=Sanchez|first15=B. K.|last15=Wang|first16=A.|last16=Bansil|first17=F.-C.|last17=Chou|first18=P. P.|last18=Shibayev|first19=H.|last19=Lin|first20=S.|last20=Jia|first21=M. Z.|last21=Hasan|title=Discovery of a Weyl Fermion semimetal and topological Fermi arcs|journal=Science|date=2015|doi=10.1126/science.aaa9297|pmid=26184916|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/early/2015/07/15/science.aaa9297.abstract|volume=349|issue=6248|pages=613\u2013617|arxiv = 1502.03807 |bibcode = 2015Sci...349..613X }}</ref><ref name=\"PhysRevX.5.031023\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevX.5.031023|title=Observation of the Chiral-Anomaly-Induced Negative Magnetoresistance in 3D Weyl Semimetal Ta ''As''|journal=Physical Review X|volume=5|issue=3|pages=031023|year=2015|last1=Huang|first1=Xiaochun|last2=Zhao|first2=Lingxiao|last3=Long|first3=Yujia|last4=Wang|first4=Peipei|last5=Chen|first5=Dong|last6=Yang|first6=Zhanhai|last7=Liang|first7=Hui|last8=Xue|first8=Mianqi|last9=Weng|first9=Hongming|last10=Fang|first10=Zhong|last11=Dai|first11=Xi|last12=Chen|first12=Genfu|arxiv=1503.01304|bibcode=2015PhRvX...5c1023H}}</ref> strontium silicide (SrSi<math>_2</math>)<ref name=\"Huang1180WeylSM\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.1514581113|pmid=26787914|pmc=4747715|title=New type of Weyl semimetal with quadratic double Weyl fermions|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=113|issue=5|pages=1180\u20135|year=2016|last1=Huang|first1=Shin-Ming|last2=Xu|first2=Su-Yang|last3=Belopolski|first3=Ilya|last4=Lee|first4=Chi-Cheng|last5=Chang|first5=Guoqing|last6=Chang|first6=Tay-Rong|last7=Wang|first7=Baokai|last8=Alidoust|first8=Nasser|last9=Bian|first9=Guang|last10=Neupane|first10=Madhab|last11=Sanchez|first11=Daniel|last12=Zheng|first12=Hao|last13=Jeng|first13=Horng-Tay|last14=Bansil|first14=Arun|last15=Neupert|first15=Titus|last16=Lin|first16=Hsin|last17=Hasan|first17=M. Zahid|arxiv=1503.05868|bibcode=2016PNAS..113.1180H}}</ref> have a Hamiltonian that is very similar to that of graphene, but now includes all three Pauli matrices and the linear crossings occur in 3D:\n:<math>\n{\\cal H} = \\hbar v_D (k_x\\sigma_x + k_y\\sigma_y + k_z\\sigma_z).\n</math>\nSince all three [[Pauli matrices]] are present, there is no further Pauli matrix that could open a gap in the spectrum and Weyl points are therefore [[topologically protected]].<ref name=\"wehling2014dirac\"/> Tilting of the linear cones so the Dirac velocity varies leads to type II Weyl semimetals.<ref name=\"soluyanov2015type\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nature15768|pmid=26607545|title=Type-II Weyl semimetals|journal=Nature|volume=527|issue=7579|pages=495\u20138|year=2015|last1=Soluyanov|first1=Alexey A|last2=Gresch|first2=Dominik|last3=Wang|first3=Zhijun|last4=Wu|first4=Quansheng|last5=Troyer|first5=Matthias|last6=Dai|first6=Xi|last7=Bernevig|first7=B. Andrei|arxiv=1507.01603|bibcode=2015Natur.527..495S}}</ref><ref name=\"Trescher2017\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.95.045139|title=Tilted disordered Weyl semimetals|journal=Physical Review B|volume=95|issue=4|pages=045139|year=2017|last1=Trescher|first1=Maximilian|last2=Sbierski|first2=Bj\u00f6rn|last3=Brouwer|first3=Piet W|last4=Bergholtz|first4=Emil J|arxiv=1611.02513|bibcode=2017PhRvB..95d5139T}}</ref>\nOne distinct, experimentally observable feature of Weyl semimetals is that the surface states form [[Fermi arc]]s since the [[Fermi surface]] does not form a closed loop.\n\n=== Dirac semimetals ===\nIn crystals that are symmetric under [[point reflection|inversion]] and [[T-symmetry|time reversal]], electronic energy bands are two-fold degenerate. This degeneracy is referred to as [[Kramers degeneracy]]. Therefore, semimetals with linear crossings of two energy bands (two-fold degeneracy) at the [[Fermi energy]] exhibit a four-fold degeneracy at the crossing point. The effective [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]] for these states can be written as \n:<math>\n{\\cal H} = \\hbar v_D \\left(\n\\begin{array}{cc}\n \\vec{k}\\cdot\\vec{\\sigma} & 0 \\\\\n 0 & -\\vec{k}\\cdot\\vec{\\sigma}\n\\end{array}\n\\right).\n</math>\nThis has exactly the matrix structure of Dirac matter. Examples of experimentally realised Dirac semimetals are [[Bismuth#Bismuthine and bismuthides|sodium bismuthide]] (Na<math>_3</math>Bi)<ref name=\"wang2012dirac\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.85.195320|title=Dirac semimetal and topological phase transitions inA3Bi (A=Na, K, Rb)|journal=Physical Review B|volume=85|issue=19|pages=195320|year=2012|last1=Wang|first1=Zhijun|last2=Sun|first2=Yan|last3=Chen|first3=Xing-Qiu|last4=Franchini|first4=Cesare|last5=Xu|first5=Gang|last6=Weng|first6=Hongming|last7=Dai|first7=Xi|last8=Fang|first8=Zhong|bibcode=2012PhRvB..85s5320W|arxiv=1202.5636}}</ref><ref name=\"liu2014discovery\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.1245085|pmid=24436183|title=Discovery of a Three-Dimensional Topological Dirac Semimetal, Na3Bi|journal=Science|volume=343|issue=6173|pages=864\u20137|year=2014|last1=Liu|first1=Z. K|last2=Zhou|first2=B|last3=Zhang|first3=Y|last4=Wang|first4=Z. J|last5=Weng|first5=H. M|last6=Prabhakaran|first6=D|last7=Mo|first7=S.- K|last8=Shen|first8=Z. X|last9=Fang|first9=Z|last10=Dai|first10=X|last11=Hussain|first11=Z|last12=Chen|first12=Y. L|arxiv=1310.0391|bibcode=2014Sci...343..864L}}</ref><ref name=\"Dirac_Xu\">{{cite journal|title=Observation of Fermi arc surface states in a topological metal|journal=Science|volume=347|issue=6219|pages=294\u20138|year=2014|last1=Xu|first1=Su-Yang|last2=Liu|first2=Chang|last3=Kushwaha|first3=Satya K.|last4=Sankar|first4=Raman|last5=Krizan|first5=Jason W.|last6=Belopolski|first6=Ilya|last7=Neupane|first7=Madhab|last8=Bian|first8=Guang|last9=Nasser|first9=Alidoust|last10=Chang|first10=Tay-Rong|last11=Jeng|first11=Horng-Tay|last12=Huang|first12=Cheng-Yi|last13=Tsai|first13=Wei-Feng|last14=Lin|first14=Hsin|last15=Shibayev|first15=Pavel P.|last16=Chou|first16=Fang-Cheng|last17=Cava|first17=Robert J.|last18=Hasan|first18=M. Zahid|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/347/6219/294.abstract}}</ref> and [[cadmium arsenide]] (Cd<math>_3</math>As<math>_2</math>)<ref name=\"Wang\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.88.125427|title=Three-dimensional Dirac semimetal and quantum transport in Cd3As2|journal=Physical Review B|volume=88|issue=12|pages=125427|year=2013|last1=Wang|first1=Zhijun|last2=Weng|first2=Hongming|last3=Wu|first3=Quansheng|last4=Dai|first4=Xi|last5=Fang|first5=Zhong|arxiv=1305.6780|bibcode=2013PhRvB..88l5427W}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Madhab\">{{cite journal|title=Observation of a three-dimensional topological Dirac semimetal phase in high-mobility Cd3As2|journal=Nature Communications|volume=5|pages=3786|year=2014|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/ncomms4786|last1=Neupane|first1=Madhab|last2=Xu|first2=Su-Yang|last3=Sankar|first3=Raman|last4=Nasser|first4=Alidoust|last5=Bian|first5=Guang|last6=Liu|first6=Chang|last7=Belopolski|first7=Ilya|last8=Chang|first8=Tay-Rong|last9=Jeng|first9=Horng-Tay|last10=Lin|first10=Hsin|last11=Bansil|first11=Aron|last12=Chou|first12=Fang-Cheng|last13=Hasan|first13=M. Zahid}}</ref><ref name=\"Borisenko\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.113.027603|pmid=25062235|title=Experimental Realization of a Three-Dimensional Dirac Semimetal|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=113|issue=2|pages=027603|year=2014|last1=Borisenko|first1=Sergey|last2=Gibson|first2=Quinn|last3=Evtushinsky|first3=Danil|last4=Zabolotnyy|first4=Volodymyr|last5=B\u00fcchner|first5=Bernd|last6=Cava|first6=Robert J|arxiv=1309.7978|bibcode=2014PhRvL.113b7603B}}</ref>\n\n== Bosonic Dirac matter ==\n[[File:Dispersions for bosonic (left) and fermionic (right) Dirac materials.png|thumb|Dispersions for bosonic (left) and fermionic (right) Dirac materials. In contrast to the fermionic case where Pauli exclusion confines excitations close to the Fermi energy, the description of boson requires the entire Brillioun zone.]]\nWhile historic interest focussed on fermionic quasiparticles that have potential for technological applications, particularly in electronics, the mathematical structure of the [[Dirac equation]] is not restricted to the [[Particle statistics|statistics of the particles]]. This has led to recent development of the concept of bosonic Dirac matter.\n\nIn the case of [[bosons]], there is no [[Pauli exclusion principle]] to confine excitations close to the [[chemical potential]] (Fermi energy for fermions) so the entire [[Brillouin zone]] must be included. At low temperatures, the bosons will collect at the lowest energy point, the <math>\\Gamma</math>-point of the lower band. Energy must be added to excite the quasiparticles to the vicinity of the linear crossing point.\n\nSeveral examples of Dirac matter with fermionic quasi-particles occur in systems where there is a hexagonal crystal lattice; so bosonic quasiparticles on an hexagonal lattice are the natural candidates for bosonic Dirac matter. In fact, the underlying symmetry of a crystal structure strongly constrains and protects the emergence of linear band crossings. Typical bosonic [[quasiparticles]] in [[condensed matter]] are [[magnon]]s, [[phonons]], [[polaritons]] and [[plasmons]].\n\nExisting examples of bosonic Dirac matter include transition metal [[halides]] such as CrX<math>_3</math> (X= Cl, Br, I), where the [[magnon]] spectrum exhibits linear crossings,<ref name=\"pershoguba2018dirac\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevX.8.011010|title=Dirac Magnons in Honeycomb Ferromagnets|journal=Physical Review X|volume=8|issue=1|pages=011010|year=2018|last1=Pershoguba|first1=Sergey S|last2=Banerjee|first2=Saikat|last3=Lashley|first3=J.\u2009C|last4=Park|first4=Jihwey|last5=\u00c5gren|first5=Hans|last6=Aeppli|first6=Gabriel|last7=Balatsky|first7=Alexander V|arxiv=1706.03384|bibcode=2018PhRvX...8a1010P}}</ref> granular [[superconductors]] in a [[honeycomb lattice]] <ref name=\"Banerjee\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.93.134502|title=Granular superconductor in a honeycomb lattice as a realization of bosonic Dirac material|journal=Physical Review B|volume=93|issue=13|pages=134502|year=2016|last1=Banerjee|first1=S|last2=Fransson|first2=J|last3=Black-Schaffer|first3=A. M|last4=\u00c5gren|first4=H|last5=Balatsky|first5=A. V|arxiv=1511.05282|bibcode=2016PhRvB..93m4502B}}</ref> and hexagonal arrays of [[semiconductor microcavities]] hosting [[microcavity polaritons]] with linear crossings.<ref name=\"jacqmin2014direct\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.112.116402|pmid=24702392|title=Direct Observation of Dirac Cones and a Flatband in a Honeycomb Lattice for Polaritons|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=112|issue=11|pages=116402|year=2014|last1=Jacqmin|first1=T|last2=Carusotto|first2=I|last3=Sagnes|first3=I|last4=Abbarchi|first4=M|last5=Solnyshkov|first5=D.\u2009D|last6=Malpuech|first6=G|last7=Galopin|first7=E|last8=Lema\u00eetre|first8=A|last9=Bloch|first9=J|last10=Amo|first10=A|arxiv=1310.8105|bibcode=2014PhRvL.112k6402J}}</ref> Like graphene, all these systems have an hexagonal lattice structure.\n\n== Anyonic Dirac materials ==\nAnyonic Dirac matter is a hypothetical field which is rather unexplored to date. An [[anyon]] is a type of quasiparticle that can only occur in two-dimensional systems. Considering [[bosons]] and [[fermions]], the interchange of two particles contributes a factor of 1 or -1 to the wave function. In contrast, the operation of exchanging two identical anyons causes a global phase shift. Anyons are generally classified as ''abelian'' or ''non-abelian,'' according to whether the elementary excitations of the theory transform under an [[abelian group|abelian]] [[group representation|representation]] of the [[braid group]] or a non-abelian one.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/0550-3213(91)90407-O |url=http://www.physics.rutgers.edu/~gmoore/MooreReadNonabelions.pdf |title=Nonabelions in the fractional quantum hall effect |date=19 Aug 1991 |last1=Moore |first1=Gregory |authorlink1=Greg Moore (physicist) |last2=Read |first2=Nicholas |authorlink2=Nicholas Read |journal=Nuclear Physics B |volume=360 |issue=2\u20133 |pages=362\u2013396 |bibcode=1991NuPhB.360..362M }}</ref> Abelian anyons have been detected in connection to the [[fractional quantum Hall effect]]. The possible construction of anyonic Dirac matter relies on the symmetry protection of crossings of anyonic energy bands. In comparison to bosons and fermions the situation gets more complicated as translations in space do not necessarily commute. Additionally, for given spatial symmetries, the group structure describing the anyon strongly depends on the specific phase of the anyon interchange. For example, for bosons, a rotation of a particle about 2{{pi}} i.e., 360<math>^\\circ</math>, will not change its wave function. For fermions, a rotation of a particle about 2{{pi}}, will contribute a factor of <math>-1</math> to its wave function, whereas a 4{{pi}} rotation, i.e., a rotation about 720<math>^\\circ</math>, will give the same wave function as before. For anyons, an even higher degree of rotation can be necessary, e.g., 6{{pi}}, 8{{pi}}, etc., to leave the wave function invariant.\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite journal|last1=Novoselov|first1=K.S. |last2=Geim |first2=A.K.|date=2007|title=The rise of graphene|journal=Nature Materials|language=|volume=6||pages=183-191}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Hasan |first1=M. Z. |last2=Xu |first2=S.-Y. |last3=Neupane |first3=M  |title=\u201cTopological Insulators, Topological Dirac semimetals, Topological Crystalline Insulators, and Topological Kondo Insulators\u201d |journal=Book Chapter in \u201cTopological Insulators\u201d edited by F. Ortmann,  S. Roche and S. O. Valenzuela (John Wiley & Sons)|date=2015 |url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/9783527681594.ch4}}\n*{{cite web|title=Weyl fermions are spotted at long last|last=Johnston|first=Hamish|url=http://physicsworld.com/cws/article/news/2015/jul/23/weyl-fermions-are-spotted-at-long-last|date=23 July 2015|website=Physics World|accessdate=22 November 2018}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Ciudad|first=David|date=20 August 2015|title=Massless yet real|journal=Nature Materials|language=|volume=14|issue=9|pages=863|doi=10.1038/nmat4411|pmid=26288972|issn=1476-1122}}\n*{{cite web|title=Where the Weyl Things Are|last=Vishwanath|first=Ashvin|url=http://physics.aps.org/articles/v8/84|date=8 September 2015|website=APS Physics|accessdate=22 November 2018}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Jia|first1=Shuang|last2=Xu|first2=Su-Yang|last3=Hasan|first3=M. Zahid|title=Weyl semimetals, Fermi arcs and chiral anomaly|journal=Nature Materials|volume=15|pages=1140|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nmat4787|date=25 October 2016}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n[[Category:Condensed matter physics]]\n", "text_old": "{{technical|date=November 2019}}\n\nThe term '''Dirac matter''' refers to a class of [[condensed matter]] systems which can be effectively described by the [[Dirac equation]]. Even though the [[Dirac equation]] itself was formulated for [[fermions]], the quasi-particles present within Dirac matter can be of any statistics. As a consequence, Dirac matter can be distinguished in [[fermionic]], [[bosonic]] or [[anyon]]ic Dirac matter. Prominent examples of Dirac matter are [[Graphene]], [[topological insulators]], Dirac semimetals, [[Weyl semimetal]]s, various [[high-temperature superconductors]] with <math>d</math>-wave pairing and [[Helium-3|liquid Helium-3]]. The effective theory of such systems is classified by a specific choice of the [[Dirac mass]], the Dirac velocity, the [[Dirac matrices]] and the [[space-time curvature]]. The universal treatment of the class of Dirac matter in terms of an effective theory leads to a common features with respect to the [[density of states]], the [[heat capacity]] and impurity scattering.\n\n== Definition ==\nMembers of the class of Dirac matter differ significantly in nature. However, all examples of Dirac matter are unified by similarities within the algebraic structure of an effective theory describing them.\n\n=== General ===\n\nThe general definition of Dirac matter is a condensed matter system where the [[quasi-particle]] excitations can be described in curved spacetime by the generalised Dirac equation:\n:<math>\n \\left[i \\hbar v_D \\gamma^a e_a^\\mu d_\\mu(p) - m v_D^2\\right]\\Psi = 0.\n</math>\nIn the above definition <math>d_\\mu</math> denotes a [[covariant vector]] depending on the <math>(d+1)</math>-dimensional momentum <math>p</math> (<math>d</math> space <math>+ 1</math> time dimension), <math>e_a^\\mu</math> is the [[vierbein]] describing the curvature of the space, <math>m</math> the [[quasi-particle]] mass and <math>v_D</math> the Dirac velocity. Note that since in Dirac matter the Dirac equation gives the effective theory of the quasiparticles, the energy from the mass term is <math>m v_D^2</math>, not the rest mass <math>m c^2</math> of a massive particle. <math>\\gamma^\\mu</math> refers to a set of [[Dirac matrices]], where the defining for the construction is given by the anticommutation relation,\n:<math>\n  \\left\\{\\gamma^\\mu,\\gamma^\\nu \\right\\} = \\gamma^\\mu\\gamma^\\nu + \\gamma^\\nu\\gamma^\\mu = \\eta^{\\mu\\nu} I_d.\n</math>\n<math>\\eta^{\\mu\\nu}</math> is the [[Minkowski metric]] with signature (+ - - -) and <math>I_d</math> is the <math>d\\times d</math>-dimensional unit matrix.\nIn all equations, implicit summation over <math>a</math> and <math>\\mu</math> is used ([[Einstein convention]]). Furthermore, <math>\\Psi</math> is the [[wavefunction]]. The unifying feature of all Dirac matter is the matrix structure of the equation describing the quasi-particle excitations.\n\nIn the limit where <math>d_\\mu(p) = D_\\mu</math>, i.e. the [[covariant derivative]], conventional Dirac matter is obtained. However, this general definition allows the description of matter with higher order dispersion relations and in curved spacetime as long as the effective [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]] exhibits the [[matrix (mathematics)|matrix]] structure specific to the [[Dirac equation]].\n\n=== Common (conventional) ===\n\nThe majority of experimental realisations of Dirac matter to date are in the limit of <math>d_\\mu (p) = D_\\mu</math> which therefore defines conventional Dirac matter in which the quasiparticles are described by the [[Dirac equation in curved spacetime|Dirac equation in curved space-time]],\n:<math>\n \\left[i \\hbar v_D \\gamma^a e_a^\\mu D_\\mu - m v_D^2\\right]\\Psi = 0.\n</math>\nHere, <math>D_\\mu</math> denotes the [[covariant derivative]]. As an example, for the flat metric, the energy of a free Dirac particle differs significantly from the classical kinetic energy where energy is proportional to momentum squared:\n:<math>\n\\begin{align}\n\\mathrm{Free~Dirac~particle: \\;} E &= \\pm \\sqrt{\\hbar^2 v_D^2\\mathbf{k}^2+m^2c^4} \\\\\n\\mathrm{Kinetic\\; energy: \\;} E &= \\frac{m |\\mathbf{v}|^2}{2} = \\frac{|\\mathbf{k}|^2}{2m}.\n\\end{align}\n</math>\nThe Dirac velocity <math>v_D</math> gives the gradient of the <math>E-k</math> dispersion at large momenta <math>k</math>, <math>m</math> is the mass of particle or object. In the case of massless Dirac matter, such as the fermionic quasiparticles in [[graphene]] or [[Weyl semimetal]]s, the energy-momentum relation is linear,\n:<math>\n E(\\mathbf{k}) = \\hbar v_D |\\mathbf{k}|\n</math>\n\nTherefore, conventional Dirac matter includes all systems that have a linear crossing or linear behavior in some region of the energy-momentum relation. They are characterised by features that resemble an 'X', sometimes tilted or skewed and sometimes with a gap between the upper <math>\\vee</math> and lower <math>\\wedge</math> parts (the turning points of which become rounded if the origin of the gap is a mass term).\n\nThe general features and some specific examples of conventional Dirac matter are discussed in the following sections.\n\n== General properties of Dirac matter ==\n\n=== Technological relevance and tuning of Dirac matter ===\n\n[[File:Tuning of Dirac matter.png|thumb|Tuning of Dirac matter: As the density of states is well defined, the density of states at the Fermi level (for fermionic Dirac matter) can be nicely tuned by shifting the chemical potential <math>\\mu</math>. Additionally, introducing a mass term <math>m</math> leads to a gap between the two cones and the dispersion becomes quadratic near <math>k=0</math>.]]\n\nDirac matter, especially fermionic Dirac matter has much potential for technological applications. For example, 2010's [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] was awarded to [[Andre Geim]] and [[Konstantin Novoselov]] \"for groundbreaking experiments regarding the material graphene\". Within the official press release of the [[Swedish Royal Academy of Science]] it is stated that<ref name=\"nobelprize\">[https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/2010/press.pdf The Nobel Prize in Physics 2010]</ref>\n{{Quote\n|text=\n[...] a vast variety of practical applications now appear possible including the creation of new materials and the manufacture of innovative electronics. Graphene transistors are predicted to be substantially faster than today\u2019s silicon transistors and result in more efficient computers.\n|author=Swedish Royal Academy of Science\n}}\n\nIn general, the properties of massless fermionic Dirac matter can be controlled by shifting the [[chemical potential]] by means of [[doping (semiconductor)|doping]] or within a [[field effect (semiconductor)|field effect]] setup. By tuning the [[chemical potential]], it is possible to have a precise control of the number of states present, since the [[density of states]] varies in a well-defined way with energy.\n\nAdditionally, depending on the specific realization of the Dirac material, it may be possible to introduce a mass term <math>m</math> that opens a gap in the spectrum - a [[band gap]]. In general, the mass term is the result of breaking a specific symmetry of the system. The size of the [[band gap]] can be controlled precisely by controlling the strength of the mass term.\n\n=== Density of states ===\nThe [[density of states]] of <math>d</math>-dimensional Dirac matter near the Dirac point scales as <math>N(\\epsilon)\\propto |\\epsilon|^{d-1}</math> where <math>\\epsilon</math> is the particle energy.<ref name=\"wehling2014dirac\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/00018732.2014.927109|title=Dirac materials|journal=Advances in Physics|volume=63|issue=1|page=1|year=2014|last1=Wehling|first1=T.O|last2=Black-Schaffer|first2=A.M|last3=Balatsky|first3=A.V|arxiv=1405.5774}}</ref> The vanishing density of states for quasiparticles in Dirac matter mimics [[semimetal]] physics for physical dimension <math>d>1</math>. In the two-dimensional systems such as graphene and topological insulators, the density of states gives a V shape, compared with the constant value for massive particles with dispersion <math>E=k^2/2m</math>.\n\nExperimental measurement of the density of states near the Dirac point by standard techniques such as scanning tunnelling microscopy often differ from the theoretical form due to the effects of disorder and interactions.<ref name=\"principi2011tunneling\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.ssc.2012.04.040|title=The tunneling density-of-states of interacting massless Dirac fermions|journal=Solid State Communications|volume=152|issue=15|page=1456|year=2012|last1=Principi|first1=A|last2=Polini|first2=Marco|last3=Asgari|first3=Reza|last4=MacDonald|first4=A.H|arxiv=1111.3822|bibcode=2012SSCom.152.1456P}}</ref>\n\n=== Specific heat ===\nSpecific heat, the [[heat capacity]] per unit mass, describes the energy required to change the temperature of a sample. The low-temperature electronic [[specific heat]] of Dirac matter is <math>C(T\\to 0)\\sim T^d</math> which is different from <math>C(T\\to 0)\\sim T</math> encountered for normal metals.<ref name=\"wehling2014dirac\"/> Therefore, for systems whose physical dimension is greater than 1, the specific heat can provide a clear signature of the underlying Dirac nature of the quasiparticles.\n\n=== Landau quantization ===\n[[Landau quantization]] refers to the quantization of the cyclotron orbits of charged particles in magnetic fields. As a result, the charged particles can only occupy orbits with discrete energy values, called Landau levels. For 2-dimensional systems with a perpendicular magnetic field, the energy for Landau-levels for ordinary matter described the Schr\u00f6dinger equation and Dirac matter are given by<ref name=\"wehling2014dirac\"/>\n:<math>\n\\begin{align}\n\\mathrm{Ordinary\\;matter: \\;} E &= \\hbar \\omega_c \\left(n+\\frac{1}{2} \\right), \\\\\n\\mathrm{Dirac\\;Matter: \\;} E &= \\hbar \\omega_c \\sqrt{|n|}.\n\\end{align}\n</math>\nHere, <math>\\omega_c</math> is the [[cyclotron frequency]] which is linearly dependent of the applied magnetic field and the charge of the particle. There are two distinct features between the Landau level quantization for 2D Schr\u00f6dinger fermions (ordinary matter) and 2D Dirac fermions. First, the energy for Schr\u00f6dinger fermions is linearly dependent with respect to the integer quantum number <math>n</math>, whereas it exhibits a square-root dependence for the Dirac fermions. This key difference plays an important role in the experimental verification of Dirac matter.<ref name=\"novoselov2005two\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nature04233|pmid=16281030|title=Two-dimensional gas of massless Dirac fermions in graphene|journal=Nature|volume=438|issue=7065|pages=197\u2013200|year=2005|last1=Novoselov|first1=K. S|last2=Geim|first2=A. K|last3=Morozov|first3=S. V|last4=Jiang|first4=D|last5=Katsnelson|first5=M. I|last6=Grigorieva|first6=I. V|last7=Dubonos|first7=S. V|last8=Firsov|first8=A. A|arxiv=cond-mat/0509330|bibcode=2005Natur.438..197N|hdl=2066/33126}}</ref><ref name=\"li2007observation\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nphys653|title=Observation of Landau levels of Dirac fermions in graphite|journal=Nature Physics|volume=3|issue=9|page=623|year=2007|last1=Li|first1=Guohong|last2=Andrei|first2=Eva Y|arxiv=0705.1185|bibcode=2007NatPh...3..623L}}</ref> Furthermore, for <math>n=0</math> there exists a 0 energy level for Dirac fermions which is independent of the cyclotron frequency <math>\\omega_c</math> and with that of the applied magnetic field. For example, the existence of the zeroth Landau level gives rise to a [[quantum Hall effect]] where the Hall conductance in quantized at half-integer values.<ref name=\"chen2008charged\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nphys935|title=Charged-impurity scattering in graphene|journal=Nature Physics|volume=4|issue=5|page=377|year=2008|last1=Chen|first1=J.-H|last2=Jang|first2=C|last3=Adam|first3=S|last4=Fuhrer|first4=M. S|last5=Williams|first5=E. D|last6=Ishigami|first6=M|arxiv=0708.2408|bibcode=2008NatPh...4..377C}}</ref><ref name=\"wehling2014dirac\"/>\n\n== Fermionic Dirac matter ==\nIn the context of Fermionic quasiparticles, the Dirac velocity is identical to the Fermi velocity; in bosonic systems, no Fermi velocity exists, so the Dirac velocity is a more general property of such systems.\n\n=== Graphene ===\n[[Graphene]] is a 2-dimensional crystalline [[allotrope]] of [[carbon]], where the carbon atoms are arranged on a [[hexagonal lattice]].\nEach carbon atom forms <math>\\sigma</math>-bonds to the three neighboring atoms that lie in the graphene plane at angles of 120<math>^\\circ</math>. These bonds are mediated by three of carbon's four [[electrons]] while the fourth electron, which occupies a <math>\\mathrm{p}_z</math> [[Atomic orbital|orbital]], mediates an out-of-plane [[pi-bond|{{pi}}-bond]] that leads to the [[Electronic band structure|electronic bands]] at the [[Fermi level]]. The unique transport properties and the [[semimetal]]lic state of graphene are the result of the delocalized electrons occupying these p<math>_z</math> orbitals.<ref name=\"abergel2010properties\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/00018732.2010.487978|title=Properties of graphene: A theoretical perspective|journal=Advances in Physics|volume=59|issue=4|pages=261\u2013482|year=2010|last1=Abergel|first1=D.S.L|last2=Apalkov|first2=V|last3=Berashevich|first3=J|last4=Ziegler|first4=K|last5=Chakraborty|first5=Tapash|arxiv=1003.0391}}</ref>\n\nThe semimetallic state corresponds to a linear crossing of energy bands at the <math>K</math> and <math>K'</math> points of graphene's hexagonal [[Brillouin zone]]. At these two points, the electronic structure can be effectively described by the [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]]\n:<math>\n{\\cal H} = \\hbar v_D \\left(\\tau k_x \\sigma_x + k_y \\sigma_y \\right). \n</math>\nHere, <math>\\sigma_x</math> and <math>\\sigma_y</math> are two of the three [[Pauli matrices]].\nThe factor <math>\\tau=+/-</math> indicates whether the Hamiltonian describes is centred on the <math>K</math> or <math>K'</math> valley at the corner of hexagonal [[Brillouin zone]]. For graphene, the Dirac velocity is about <math>\\hbar v_D \\approx 5.8</math> eV <math>\\AA</math>.<ref name=\"abergel2010properties\"/> An energy gap in the dispersion of graphene can be obtained from a low-energy Hamiltionain of the form \n:<math>\n\\begin{align}\n{\\cal H} = \\hbar v_D (\\tau k_x \\sigma_x + k_y\\sigma_y) + M \\sigma_z,\n\\end{align}\n</math>\nwhich now contains a mass term <math>M</math>. There are several distinct ways of introducing a mass term, and the results have different characteristics.<ref name=\"haldane\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.61.2015|pmid=10038961|title=Model for a Quantum Hall Effect without Landau Levels: Condensed-Matter Realization of the \"Parity Anomaly\"|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=61|issue=18|pages=2015\u20132018|year=1988|last1=Haldane|first1=F. D. M|bibcode=1988PhRvL..61.2015H|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"kane-mele\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.95.226801|pmid=16384250|title=Quantum Spin Hall Effect in Graphene|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=95|issue=22|pages=226801|year=2005|last1=Kane|first1=C. L|last2=Mele|first2=E. J|arxiv=cond-mat/0411737|bibcode=2005PhRvL..95v6801K}}</ref> The most practical approach for creating a gap (introducing a mass term) is to break the sublattice symmetry of the lattice where each carbon atom is slightly different to its nearest but identical to its next-nearest neighbours; an effect that may result from substrate effects.\n\n=== Topological insulators ===\nA [[topological insulator]] is a material that behaves as an insulator in its interior (bulk) but whose surface contains conducting states. This property represents a non-trivial, symmetry protected [[topological order]]. As a consequence, electrons in topological insulators can only move along the [[Interface (matter)|surface]] of the material. In the bulk of a non-interacting topological insulator, the [[Fermi level]] is positioned within the gap between the [[valence and conduction bands|conduction and valence bands]]. On the surface, there are special states within the bulk [[energy gap]] which can be effectively described by a Dirac Hamiltonian: \n:<math>\n\\begin{align}\n{\\cal H} = \\hbar v_{D} (\\mathbf{k}\\times \\mathbf{\\sigma})\\cdot\\hat{\\mathbf{z}}\n\\end{align}\n</math>\nwhere <math>\\hat{\\mathbf{z}}</math> is normal to the surface and <math>{\\mathbf{\\sigma}}</math> is in the real [[spin (physics)|spin]] basis. However, if we rotate spin by a [[unitary operator]], <math>U={\\rm diag}[1,i]</math>, we will end up with the standard notation of Dirac Hamiltonian, <math>{\\cal H} = \\hbar v_{D} {\\mathbf{\\sigma}}\\cdot {\\mathbf{k}}</math>.   \nSuch Dirac cones emerging on the surface of 3-dimensional crystals were observed in experiment, e.g.: [[bismuth selenide]] (Bi<math>_2</math>Se<math>_3</math>),<ref name=\"xia2009observation\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nphys1274|title=Observation of a large-gap topological-insulator class with a single Dirac cone on the surface|journal=Nature Physics|volume=5|issue=6|pages=398\u2013402|year=2009|last1=Xia|first1=Y|last2=Qian|first2=D|last3=Hsieh|first3=D|last4=Wray|first4=L|last5=Pal|first5=A|last6=Lin|first6=H|last7=Bansil|first7=A|last8=Grauer|first8=D|last9=Hor|first9=Y. S|last10=Cava|first10=R. J|last11=Hasan|first11=M. Z|arxiv=0908.3513|bibcode=2009NatPh...5..398X}}</ref> [[tin telluride]] (SnTe).<ref name=\"tanaka2012experimental\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nphys2442|title=Experimental realization of a topological crystalline insulator in Sn ''Te''|journal=Nature Physics|volume=8|issue=11|page=800|year=2012|last1=Tanaka|first1=Y|last2=Ren|first2=Zhi|last3=Sato|first3=T|last4=Nakayama|first4=K|last5=Souma|first5=S|last6=Takahashi|first6=T|last7=Segawa|first7=Kouji|last8=Ando|first8=Yoichi|arxiv=1206.5399|bibcode=2012NatPh...8..800T}}</ref>\n\n=== Transition metal dichalcogenides (TMDCs) ===\n[[File:Dispersions of transition metal dichalcogenides.png|thumb|While they are gapped, near the <math>K</math> and <math>K^\\prime</math> points of their hexagonal Brilliouin zone, the dispersions of transition metal dichalcogenides can be described by a massive Dirac equation with additional spin-orbit coupling terms that lead to spin-splitting in the valence band.]]\nThe low-energy properties some semiconducting [[transition metal dichalcogenide monolayers]],\ncan be described by a two-dimensional massive (gapped) Dirac Hamiltonian with an additional term describing a strong [[spin\u2013orbit coupling]]:<ref name=\"Xiao12\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.108.196802|pmid=23003071|title=Coupled Spin and Valley Physics in Monolayers ofMoS2and Other Group-VI Dichalcogenides|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=108|issue=19|pages=196802|year=2012|last1=Xiao|first1=Di|last2=Liu|first2=Gui-Bin|last3=Feng|first3=Wanxiang|last4=Xu|first4=Xiaodong|last5=Yao|first5=Wang|arxiv=1112.3144|bibcode=2012PhRvL.108s6802X}}</ref><ref name=\"rostami_prb_2013\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.88.085440|title=Effective lattice Hamiltonian for monolayer MoS2: Tailoring electronic structure with perpendicular electric and magnetic fields|journal=Physical Review B|volume=88|issue=8|pages=085440|year=2013|last1=Rostami|first1=Habib|last2=Moghaddam|first2=Ali G|last3=Asgari|first3=Reza|arxiv=1302.5901|bibcode=2013PhRvB..88h5440R}}</ref><ref name=\"Andor_prb_2013\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.88.045416|title=Monolayer MoS2: Trigonal warping, the\u0393valley, and spin-orbit coupling effects|journal=Physical Review B|volume=88|issue=4|pages=045416|year=2013|last1=Korm\u00e1nyos|first1=Andor|last2=Z\u00f3lyomi|first2=Viktor|last3=Drummond|first3=Neil D|last4=Rakyta|first4=P\u00e9ter|last5=Burkard|first5=Guido|last6=Fal'Ko|first6=Vladimir I|arxiv=1304.4084|bibcode=2013PhRvB..88d5416K}}</ref><ref name=\"Liu_prb_2013\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.88.085433|title=Three-band tight-binding model for monolayers of group-VIB transition metal dichalcogenides|journal=Physical Review B|volume=88|issue=8|pages=085433|year=2013|last1=Liu|first1=Gui-Bin|last2=Shan|first2=Wen-Yu|last3=Yao|first3=Yugui|last4=Yao|first4=Wang|last5=Xiao|first5=Di|arxiv=1305.6089|bibcode=2013PhRvB..88h5433L}}</ref> \n:<math>\n\\begin{align}\n{\\cal H} = \\hbar v_{D} (\\tau k_x \\sigma_x+k_y\\sigma_y)+\\Delta\\sigma_z+\\lambda(1-\\sigma_z)\\tau s+(\\alpha+\\beta\\sigma_z)(k_x^2+k_y^2).\n\\end{align}\n</math>\n\nThe spin-orbit coupling <math>\\lambda</math> provides a large spin-splitting in the valence band and <math>s</math> indicates the [[spin (physics)|spin]] degree of freedom. As for graphene, <math>\\tau</math> gives the valley degree of freedom - whether near the <math>K</math> or <math>K^\\prime</math> point of the hexagonal Brillouin zone. Transition metal dichalcogenide monolayers are often discussed in reference to potential applications in [[valleytronics]].\n\n=== Weyl semimetals ===\n[[Weyl semimetal]]s, for example tantalum arsenide (TaAs),<ref name=Huang>{{cite journal|last1=Huang|first1=S.-M.|first2=S.-Y.|last2=Xu|first3=I.|last3=Belopolski|first4=C.-C.|last4=Lee|first5=G.|last5=Chang|first6=B. K.|last6=Wang|first7=N.|last7=Alidoust|first8=G.|last8=Bian|first9=M.|last9=Neupane|first10=C.|last10=Zhang|first11=S.|last11=Jia|first12=A.|last12=Bansil|first13=H.|last13=Lin|first14=M. Z.|last14=Hasan|title=A Weyl Fermion semimetal with surface Fermi arcs in the transition metal monopnictide TaAs class|journal=Nature Communications|date=2015|volume=6|page=7373|doi=10.1038/ncomms8373|pmid=26067579|pmc=4490374|bibcode = 2015NatCo...6.7373H }}</ref><ref name=\"PhysRevX.5.011029\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevX.5.011029|title=Weyl Semimetal Phase in Noncentrosymmetric Transition-Metal Monophosphides|journal=Physical Review X|volume=5|issue=1|pages=011029|year=2015|last1=Weng|first1=Hongming|last2=Fang|first2=Chen|last3=Fang|first3=Zhong|last4=Bernevig|first4=B. Andrei|last5=Dai|first5=Xi|arxiv=1501.00060|bibcode=2015PhRvX...5a1029W}}</ref><ref name=Xu>{{cite journal|last1=Xu|first1=S.-Y.|first2=I.|last2=Belopolski|first3=N.|last3=Alidoust|first4=M.|last4=Neupane|first5=G.|last5=Bian|first6=C.|last6=Zhang|first7=R.|last7=Sankar|first8=G.|last8=Chang|first9=Z.|last9=Yuan|first10=C.-C.|last10=Lee|first11=S.-M.|last11=Huang|first12=H.|last12=Zheng|first13=J.|last13=Ma|first14=D. S.|last14=Sanchez|first15=B. K.|last15=Wang|first16=A.|last16=Bansil|first17=F.-C.|last17=Chou|first18=P. P.|last18=Shibayev|first19=H.|last19=Lin|first20=S.|last20=Jia|first21=M. Z.|last21=Hasan|title=Discovery of a Weyl Fermion semimetal and topological Fermi arcs|journal=Science|date=2015|doi=10.1126/science.aaa9297|pmid=26184916|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/early/2015/07/15/science.aaa9297.abstract|volume=349|issue=6248|pages=613\u2013617|arxiv = 1502.03807 |bibcode = 2015Sci...349..613X }}</ref><ref name=\"PhysRevX.5.031023\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevX.5.031023|title=Observation of the Chiral-Anomaly-Induced Negative Magnetoresistance in 3D Weyl Semimetal Ta ''As''|journal=Physical Review X|volume=5|issue=3|pages=031023|year=2015|last1=Huang|first1=Xiaochun|last2=Zhao|first2=Lingxiao|last3=Long|first3=Yujia|last4=Wang|first4=Peipei|last5=Chen|first5=Dong|last6=Yang|first6=Zhanhai|last7=Liang|first7=Hui|last8=Xue|first8=Mianqi|last9=Weng|first9=Hongming|last10=Fang|first10=Zhong|last11=Dai|first11=Xi|last12=Chen|first12=Genfu|arxiv=1503.01304|bibcode=2015PhRvX...5c1023H}}</ref> strontium silicide (SrSi<math>_2</math>)<ref name=\"Huang1180WeylSM\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.1514581113|pmid=26787914|pmc=4747715|title=New type of Weyl semimetal with quadratic double Weyl fermions|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=113|issue=5|pages=1180\u20135|year=2016|last1=Huang|first1=Shin-Ming|last2=Xu|first2=Su-Yang|last3=Belopolski|first3=Ilya|last4=Lee|first4=Chi-Cheng|last5=Chang|first5=Guoqing|last6=Chang|first6=Tay-Rong|last7=Wang|first7=Baokai|last8=Alidoust|first8=Nasser|last9=Bian|first9=Guang|last10=Neupane|first10=Madhab|last11=Sanchez|first11=Daniel|last12=Zheng|first12=Hao|last13=Jeng|first13=Horng-Tay|last14=Bansil|first14=Arun|last15=Neupert|first15=Titus|last16=Lin|first16=Hsin|last17=Hasan|first17=M. Zahid|arxiv=1503.05868|bibcode=2016PNAS..113.1180H}}</ref> have a Hamiltonian that is very similar to that of graphene, but now includes all three Pauli matrices and the linear crossings occur in 3D:\n:<math>\n{\\cal H} = \\hbar v_D (k_x\\sigma_x + k_y\\sigma_y + k_z\\sigma_z).\n</math>\nSince all three [[Pauli matrices]] are present, there is no further Pauli matrix that could open a gap in the spectrum and Weyl points are therefore [[topologically protected]].<ref name=\"wehling2014dirac\"/> Tilting of the linear cones so the Dirac velocity varies leads to type II Weyl semimetals.<ref name=\"soluyanov2015type\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nature15768|pmid=26607545|title=Type-II Weyl semimetals|journal=Nature|volume=527|issue=7579|pages=495\u20138|year=2015|last1=Soluyanov|first1=Alexey A|last2=Gresch|first2=Dominik|last3=Wang|first3=Zhijun|last4=Wu|first4=Quansheng|last5=Troyer|first5=Matthias|last6=Dai|first6=Xi|last7=Bernevig|first7=B. Andrei|arxiv=1507.01603|bibcode=2015Natur.527..495S}}</ref><ref name=\"Trescher2017\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.95.045139|title=Tilted disordered Weyl semimetals|journal=Physical Review B|volume=95|issue=4|pages=045139|year=2017|last1=Trescher|first1=Maximilian|last2=Sbierski|first2=Bj\u00f6rn|last3=Brouwer|first3=Piet W|last4=Bergholtz|first4=Emil J|arxiv=1611.02513|bibcode=2017PhRvB..95d5139T}}</ref>\nOne distinct, experimentally observable feature of Weyl semimetals is that the surface states form [[Fermi arc]]s since the [[Fermi surface]] does not form a closed loop.\n\n=== Dirac semimetals ===\nIn crystals that are symmetric under [[point reflection|inversion]] and [[T-symmetry|time reversal]], electronic energy bands are two-fold degenerate. This degeneracy is referred to as [[Kramers degeneracy]]. Therefore, semimetals with linear crossings of two energy bands (two-fold degeneracy) at the [[Fermi energy]] exhibit a four-fold degeneracy at the crossing point. The effective [[Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)|Hamiltonian]] for these states can be written as \n:<math>\n{\\cal H} = \\hbar v_D \\left(\n\\begin{array}{cc}\n \\vec{k}\\cdot\\vec{\\sigma} & 0 \\\\\n 0 & -\\vec{k}\\cdot\\vec{\\sigma}\n\\end{array}\n\\right).\n</math>\nThis has exactly the matrix structure of Dirac matter. Examples of experimentally realised Dirac semimetals are [[Bismuth#Bismuthine and bismuthides|sodium bismuthide]] (Na<math>_3</math>Bi)<ref name=\"wang2012dirac\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.85.195320|title=Dirac semimetal and topological phase transitions inA3Bi (A=Na, K, Rb)|journal=Physical Review B|volume=85|issue=19|pages=195320|year=2012|last1=Wang|first1=Zhijun|last2=Sun|first2=Yan|last3=Chen|first3=Xing-Qiu|last4=Franchini|first4=Cesare|last5=Xu|first5=Gang|last6=Weng|first6=Hongming|last7=Dai|first7=Xi|last8=Fang|first8=Zhong|bibcode=2012PhRvB..85s5320W|arxiv=1202.5636}}</ref><ref name=\"liu2014discovery\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.1245085|pmid=24436183|title=Discovery of a Three-Dimensional Topological Dirac Semimetal, Na3Bi|journal=Science|volume=343|issue=6173|pages=864\u20137|year=2014|last1=Liu|first1=Z. K|last2=Zhou|first2=B|last3=Zhang|first3=Y|last4=Wang|first4=Z. J|last5=Weng|first5=H. M|last6=Prabhakaran|first6=D|last7=Mo|first7=S.- K|last8=Shen|first8=Z. X|last9=Fang|first9=Z|last10=Dai|first10=X|last11=Hussain|first11=Z|last12=Chen|first12=Y. L|arxiv=1310.0391|bibcode=2014Sci...343..864L}}</ref><ref name=\"Dirac_Xu\">{{cite journal|title=Observation of Fermi arc surface states in a topological metal|journal=Science|volume=347|issue=6219|pages=294\u20138|year=2014|last1=Xu|first1=Su-Yang|last2=Liu|first2=Chang|last3=Kushwaha|first3=Satya K.|last4=Sankar|first4=Raman|last5=Krizan|first5=Jason W.|last6=Belopolski|first6=Ilya|last7=Neupane|first7=Madhab|last8=Bian|first8=Guang|last9=Nasser|first9=Alidoust|last10=Chang|first10=Tay-Rong|last11=Jeng|first11=Horng-Tay|last12=Huang|first12=Cheng-Yi|last13=Tsai|first13=Wei-Feng|last14=Lin|first14=Hsin|last15=Shibayev|first15=Pavel P.|last16=Chou|first16=Fang-Cheng|last17=Cava|first17=Robert J.|last18=Hasan|first18=M. Zahid|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/347/6219/294.abstract}}</ref> and [[cadmium arsenide]] (Cd<math>_3</math>As<math>_2</math>)<ref name=\"Wang\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.88.125427|title=Three-dimensional Dirac semimetal and quantum transport in Cd3As2|journal=Physical Review B|volume=88|issue=12|pages=125427|year=2013|last1=Wang|first1=Zhijun|last2=Weng|first2=Hongming|last3=Wu|first3=Quansheng|last4=Dai|first4=Xi|last5=Fang|first5=Zhong|arxiv=1305.6780|bibcode=2013PhRvB..88l5427W}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Madhab\">{{cite journal|title=Observation of a three-dimensional topological Dirac semimetal phase in high-mobility Cd3As2|journal=Nature Communications|volume=5|pages=3786|year=2014|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/ncomms4786|last1=Neupane|first1=Madhab|last2=Xu|first2=Su-Yang|last3=Sankar|first3=Raman|last4=Nasser|first4=Alidoust|last5=Bian|first5=Guang|last6=Liu|first6=Chang|last7=Belopolski|first7=Ilya|last8=Chang|first8=Tay-Rong|last9=Jeng|first9=Horng-Tay|last10=Lin|first10=Hsin|last11=Bansil|first11=Aron|last12=Chou|first12=Fang-Cheng|last13=Hasan|first13=M. Zahid}}</ref><ref name=\"Borisenko\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.113.027603|pmid=25062235|title=Experimental Realization of a Three-Dimensional Dirac Semimetal|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=113|issue=2|pages=027603|year=2014|last1=Borisenko|first1=Sergey|last2=Gibson|first2=Quinn|last3=Evtushinsky|first3=Danil|last4=Zabolotnyy|first4=Volodymyr|last5=B\u00fcchner|first5=Bernd|last6=Cava|first6=Robert J|arxiv=1309.7978|bibcode=2014PhRvL.113b7603B}}</ref>\n\n== Bosonic Dirac matter ==\n[[File:Dispersions for bosonic (left) and fermionic (right) Dirac materials.png|thumb|Dispersions for bosonic (left) and fermionic (right) Dirac materials. In contrast to the fermionic case where Pauli exclusion confines excitations close to the Fermi energy, the description of boson requires the entire Brillioun zone.]]\nWhile historic interest focussed on fermionic quasiparticles that have potential for technological applications, particularly in electronics, the mathematical structure of the [[Dirac equation]] is not restricted to the [[Particle statistics|statistics of the particles]]. This has led to recent development of the concept of bosonic Dirac matter.\n\nIn the case of [[bosons]], there is no [[Pauli exclusion principle]] to confine excitations close to the [[chemical potential]] (Fermi energy for fermions) so the entire [[Brillouin zone]] must be included. At low temperatures, the bosons will collect at the lowest energy point, the <math>\\Gamma</math>-point of the lower band. Energy must be added to excite the quasiparticles to the vicinity of the linear crossing point.\n\nSeveral examples of Dirac matter with fermionic quasi-particles occur in systems where there is a hexagonal crystal lattice; so bosonic quasiparticles on an hexagonal lattice are the natural candidates for bosonic Dirac matter. In fact, the underlying symmetry of a crystal structure strongly constrains and protects the emergence of linear band crossings. Typical bosonic [[quasiparticles]] in [[condensed matter]] are [[magnon]]s, [[phonons]], [[polaritons]] and [[plasmons]].\n\nExisting examples of bosonic Dirac matter include transition metal [[halides]] such as CrX<math>_3</math> (X= Cl, Br, I), where the [[magnon]] spectrum exhibits linear crossings,<ref name=\"pershoguba2018dirac\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevX.8.011010|title=Dirac Magnons in Honeycomb Ferromagnets|journal=Physical Review X|volume=8|issue=1|pages=011010|year=2018|last1=Pershoguba|first1=Sergey S|last2=Banerjee|first2=Saikat|last3=Lashley|first3=J.\u2009C|last4=Park|first4=Jihwey|last5=\u00c5gren|first5=Hans|last6=Aeppli|first6=Gabriel|last7=Balatsky|first7=Alexander V|arxiv=1706.03384|bibcode=2018PhRvX...8a1010P}}</ref> granular [[superconductors]] in a [[honeycomb lattice]] <ref name=\"Banerjee\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.93.134502|title=Granular superconductor in a honeycomb lattice as a realization of bosonic Dirac material|journal=Physical Review B|volume=93|issue=13|pages=134502|year=2016|last1=Banerjee|first1=S|last2=Fransson|first2=J|last3=Black-Schaffer|first3=A. M|last4=\u00c5gren|first4=H|last5=Balatsky|first5=A. V|arxiv=1511.05282|bibcode=2016PhRvB..93m4502B}}</ref> and hexagonal arrays of [[semiconductor microcavities]] hosting [[microcavity polaritons]] with linear crossings.<ref name=\"jacqmin2014direct\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.112.116402|pmid=24702392|title=Direct Observation of Dirac Cones and a Flatband in a Honeycomb Lattice for Polaritons|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=112|issue=11|pages=116402|year=2014|last1=Jacqmin|first1=T|last2=Carusotto|first2=I|last3=Sagnes|first3=I|last4=Abbarchi|first4=M|last5=Solnyshkov|first5=D.\u2009D|last6=Malpuech|first6=G|last7=Galopin|first7=E|last8=Lema\u00eetre|first8=A|last9=Bloch|first9=J|last10=Amo|first10=A|arxiv=1310.8105|bibcode=2014PhRvL.112k6402J}}</ref> Like graphene, all these systems have an hexagonal lattice structure.\n\n== Anyonic Dirac materials ==\nAnyonic Dirac matter is a hypothetical field which is rather unexplored to date. An [[anyon]] is a type of quasiparticle that can only occur in two-dimensional systems. Considering [[bosons]] and [[fermions]], the interchange of two particles contributes a factor of 1 or -1 to the wave function. In contrast, the operation of exchanging two identical anyons causes a global phase shift. Anyons are generally classified as ''abelian'' or ''non-abelian,'' according to whether the elementary excitations of the theory transform under an [[abelian group|abelian]] [[group representation|representation]] of the [[braid group]] or a non-abelian one.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/0550-3213(91)90407-O |url=http://www.physics.rutgers.edu/~gmoore/MooreReadNonabelions.pdf |title=Nonabelions in the fractional quantum hall effect |date=19 Aug 1991 |last1=Moore |first1=Gregory |authorlink1=Greg Moore (physicist) |last2=Read |first2=Nicholas |authorlink2=Nicholas Read |journal=Nuclear Physics B |volume=360 |issue=2\u20133 |pages=362\u2013396 |bibcode=1991NuPhB.360..362M }}</ref> Abelian anyons have been detected in connection to the [[fractional quantum Hall effect]]. The possible construction of anyonic Dirac matter relies on the symmetry protection of crossings of anyonic energy bands. In comparison to bosons and fermions the situation gets more complicated as translations in space do not necessarily commute. Additionally, for given spatial symmetries, the group structure describing the anyon strongly depends on the specific phase of the anyon interchange. For example, for bosons, a rotation of a particle about 2{{pi}} i.e., 360<math>^\\circ</math>, will not change its wave function. For fermions, a rotation of a particle about 2{{pi}}, will contribute a factor of <math>-1</math> to its wave function, whereas a 4{{pi}} rotation, i.e., a rotation about 720<math>^\\circ</math>, will give the same wave function as before. For anyons, an even higher degree of rotation can be necessary, e.g., 6{{pi}}, 8{{pi}}, etc., to leave the wave function invariant.\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite web|title=Weyl fermions are spotted at long last|last=Johnston|first=Hamish|url=http://physicsworld.com/cws/article/news/2015/jul/23/weyl-fermions-are-spotted-at-long-last|date=23 July 2015|website=Physics World|accessdate=22 November 2018}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Ciudad|first=David|date=20 August 2015|title=Massless yet real|journal=Nature Materials|language=|volume=14|issue=9|pages=863|doi=10.1038/nmat4411|pmid=26288972|issn=1476-1122}}\n*{{cite web|title=Where the Weyl Things Are|last=Vishwanath|first=Ashvin|url=http://physics.aps.org/articles/v8/84|date=8 September 2015|website=APS Physics|accessdate=22 November 2018}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Jia|first1=Shuang|last2=Xu|first2=Su-Yang|last3=Hasan|first3=M. Zahid|title=Weyl semimetals, Fermi arcs and chiral anomaly|journal=Nature Materials|volume=15|pages=1140|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nmat4787|date=25 October 2016}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n[[Category:Condensed matter physics]]\n", "name_user": "Graphene2010", "label": "safe", "comment": "References added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dirac_matter"}
